    <Declaration><![CDATA[(*!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
	Original Code Concept By: B.Lekx-Toniolo of Toniolo Research & Development Inc. 
	all copyright, IP and moral rights apply
	Date: July 2010.
	Fort Wisers
	S.H.H.D.I. 
	
	Major Migration from TC2 -> TC3 Platform primarily handled by Chris Drees of Sodecia GTAC 
	Date: 2020
	Major Migration from IWS -> TcHmi Platform primarily handled by c.drees and b.lekx-toniolo
	Date: 2022 - 2024
	
	
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
REVISION NOTES: 
	Date: May 2012
	- generic functionality mods: Rob Remillard
	Date: December 2012
	- Various Updates to accomodate hardware change to SSCCv4.6 and allow Kuka and Motoman use, b.lekx-toniolo
	Date: May/June 2013
	- B562 As Commisioned for AB Ring, b.lekx-toniolo and r.remillard
	Date: July 2014
	- added robot capability of up to 20 robots, JVD
	- changed to allow up to 8 ICs wherever it was missing, JVD
	Date: October 2014
	- added capability of up to 30 robots maximum (25 recommended), b.lekx-toniolo
	Date: Summer / Fall 2015
	- migration to V5.00 machines (Win7 Platform), b.lekx-toniolo
	Date: Spring 2017
	- migration to V5.03 machines (Minor changes), b.lekx-toniolo
	Date: April 2017
	- Update to Kuka FB for new Safe Space, r.remillard
	Date: Summer/Fall 2017
	- migration to v5.04 machines (Minor changes), j.vandongen
	Date: Fall 2019
	- migration to v5.05 machines (Minor changes), j.vandongen
	- revamped the EOAT section, j.vandongen
	- changed ST from Nelson to Emhart. Nelson instance stored in the FB, j.vandongen
	Date: Fall/Winter 2019-2020
	- migration to v5.06 level as follows (also see task list for details)
		>production code updates per R&D request, b.lekx-toniolo, r.remillard, c.drees
		>brought in latest servo code, b.lekx-toniolo
		>various small bug fixes as per bug fix list, b.lekx-toniolo
		>Emhart code / UI upgrades (developed by j.underhill, imported by blt)
		>EOAT code / UI upgrades (developed by j.vandongen, imported by blt)
	Date: Winter 2020-2021
	- major migration from TC2 -> TC3 platform to create V6.xx level(c.drees, b.lekx-toniolo)
		>overhaul of safety from old config type to new visual layout (c.drees)
		>minor and various updates as required by new platform (c.drees, b.lekx-toniolo)
	Date: May 2021
	-Relinked all I/O link waterstands (c.drees)
	-corrected KUKA_FB version to ensure functionality is not missing (c.drees)
	-Corrected WS_FB version to ensure that functionality is not lost (c.drees)
	-Added All WCU Stepper reset checks and Any_TipChange_Request (c.drees)
	
	Date: 2022, 2023, 2024
	- IWS to TcHMI (TcUI) migration project, creates new rev level 6.10
		> various PLC changes as a result of migration work (b.lekx-toniolo / c.drees)
		> some PLC bug fixes while co-maintaining project PLC copy and SSCC6.01 (working FW package at time) (b.lekx-toniolo / c.drees)
	   	> Added Swing Arm control FBs to Main
		> added in various chages for project 90034 (simulation integration) (b.lekx-toniolo)

	
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Some Key Notes Common to Project:
	All FBs and FUNs are 100% generic and thus exportable to other IC's of same version level (5.xx) (6.xx)
	All Prgs are custom per IPC (should not be exported)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Some Notes for general mapping from Process Flow Department:
Fix#1-99 = Fixtures with Human Interaction
Fix#101-199 = Fixtures with NO Human Interaction (internal)
etc etc

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Some notes on Commenting Conventions
	Please everyone try to comment where you make changes / additions
	Some comment formats should be used where applicable / possible

	EXAMPLES:
		(*DEBUG, blah blah blah, your initials*)
			- this type of comment should be used where you've left something in a state that the end application deployment programmer needs to confirm/check/modify etc
				once they have done what they need to do, the comment should be deleted unless it's still applicable. The machine should be as free of DE BUG type comments before
				it ships to the end customer.

		(*NOTE, bling bling bling, your initials*)
			- this type of comment should be used when a specifc area of code might be of interest or value to the next anticipated person
				for example, if you've finished off some code as far as you can but know the next user will likely build upon it, a comment like this can be used.
				you may even co-ordinate with the end user and put their name or a keyword in place so they can search specific notes left for them
				this comment should not be used if the code is left in an unfinsihed state that may cause the machine to not run, in that case a DE BUG note shall be used

thanks to j.underhill for this comment convention contribution
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
*)

